    routeSlug: "48-rotate-image",
    summary: "Given an n×n integer matrix, rotate all its elements 90 degrees clockwise in-place without allocating an auxiliary matrix.",
    approach: "- A 90° clockwise rotation can be decomposed into two simpler in-place operations: **transpose** followed by **horizontal mirror**.\n- Transposing swaps every element `matrix[i][j]` with `matrix[j][i]` (upper triangle only, to avoid double-swapping).\n- Reversing each row then shifts columns left-to-right, which is equivalent to mirroring along the vertical axis — together the two steps produce a 90° clockwise result.\n- Both passes are O(n²) and neither requires extra storage, so the solution is truly in-place.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {\n        int n = matrix.size();\n\n        // Step 1: transpose — swap matrix[i][j] with matrix[j][i]\n        // Iterate only the upper triangle to avoid double-swapping.\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)\n            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; ++j)\n                swap(matrix[i][j], matrix[j][i]);\n\n        // Step 2: reverse each row — equivalent to a horizontal flip.\n        // Transpose + horizontal flip == 90° clockwise rotation.\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)\n            reverse(matrix[i].begin(), matrix[i].end());\n    }\n};\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(n²)",
