    summary: "Given a sorted integer matrix where each row is sorted left-to-right and the first element of each row is greater than the last element of the previous row, determine whether a target value exists in the matrix.",
    approach: "- Treat the entire m×n matrix as a single sorted array of length m*n and run one binary search over virtual indices 0..m*n-1.\n- Convert a virtual mid index to a 2-D coordinate with `row = mid / n` and `col = mid % n`, then compare `matrix[row][col]` to target.\n- This works because the row-major layout of a matrix that satisfies the two sorted-order constraints is itself a fully sorted sequence.\n- One pass gives O(log(m·n)) = O(log m + log n) time with O(1) extra space.",
    code: "#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    bool searchMatrix(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int target) {\n        int m = matrix.size();\n        int n = matrix[0].size();\n\n        // Treat the matrix as a flat sorted array of length m*n.\n        int lo = 0, hi = m * n - 1;\n\n        while (lo <= hi) {\n            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;      // avoids overflow\n            int val = matrix[mid / n][mid % n]; // map flat index -> 2-D cell\n\n            if (val == target) return true;\n            if (val < target)  lo = mid + 1;\n            else               hi = mid - 1;\n        }\n\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(log(m * n))",
    spaceComplexity: "O(1)",
